Looking just at the mean and variance values for each variable it appears that all the “x” values x1, x2, x3 and x4 appear very similar.

Likewise all the “y” values y1, y2, y3 and y4 appear very similar, again, only judging by the mean and variance values.

I’m sure this won’t turn out to be the case when we visualise the data.

anscombe

Using an enhanced pairs.panel function from the "psych’ library to give a very quick indication across all of the x values and then all of the y values.

library(psych)
pairs.panels(anscombe[c("x1", "x2", "x3", "x4")])

pairs.panels(anscombe[c("y1", "y2", "y3", "y4")])

The above plot and the boxplot below shows that some datasets do vary. x1 - x3 look to have similar properties in both plots. However, x4, y1 and y2 are clearly different. y3 and y4 look similar but do have differences.

Not sure I trust the correlation figures of 0.82 for all of the (x,y) relationships.

psych::pairs.panels(anscombe[c("x1", "y1", "x2", "y2", "x3", "y3", "x4", "y4")])

Each of the plots of the (x,y) relationship between the two sets of data shows a different pattern on the scatterplot. (x1, y1) looks like you could fit a line through some of the points although some points are further away.

plot(x1 ~ y1, data = anscombe)

This plot shows a curved relation ship between the two variables.

plot(x2 ~ y2, data = anscombe)

This appears to show a straight-line relationship between the two variables but there is one significant outlier that does not fit with this.

plot(x3 ~ y3, data = anscombe)

Again, appears to show a stright-line relationship with one significant outlier.

plot(x4 ~ y4, data = anscombe)
